          <div style="font-size:0.68rem;font-weight:800;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#a78bfa;margin-bottom:12px">Test prompts to try</div>
          <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:10px;margin-bottom:20px">
            <div style="background:#f7f9ff;border:1px solid #e8eeff;border-radius:8px;padding:12px 14px">
              <div style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;color:#6c47d4;margin-bottom:4px">Start simple</div>
              <div style="font-size:0.78rem;color:#555;font-style:italic;line-height:1.5">"Here is the CUSTOMER table from our source data dictionary [paste rows]. Produce the source-to-target mapping table only."</div>
            </div>
            <div style="background:#f7f9ff;border:1px solid #e8eeff;border-radius:8px;padding:12px 14px">
              <div style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;color:#6c47d4;margin-bottom:4px">Find the traps</div>
              <div style="font-size:0.78rem;color:#555;font-style:italic;line-height:1.5">"Review the ACCOUNT table source columns and identify every column that will require a transformation — especially amount fields and date fields."</div>
            </div>
            <div style="background:#f7f9ff;border:1px solid #e8eeff;border-radius:8px;padding:12px 14px">
              <div style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;color:#6c47d4;margin-bottom:4px">Gap analysis</div>
              <div style="font-size:0.78rem;color:#555;font-style:italic;line-height:1.5">"Which source columns have no mapping in the target spec? Which target columns have no source equivalent? List both."</div>
            </div>
            <div style="background:#f7f9ff;border:1px solid #e8eeff;border-radius:8px;padding:12px 14px">
              <div style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;color:#6c47d4;margin-bottom:4px">Load order</div>
              <div style="font-size:0.78rem;color:#555;font-style:italic;line-height:1.5">"Given the FK relationships in these three tables, what is the correct load sequence? What happens if we load in the wrong order?"</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="prompt-box">
          <div class="prompt-label">Full system prompt</div>
          <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyPrompt(this)">Copy</button>
          <div class="prompt-text">You are an expert data migration analyst supporting a large banking technology transformation project. We are migrating from Oracle 12c to Azure Database for PostgreSQL 15.

Your job is to help me analyse source and target schema documentation and produce structured mapping artefacts. I will paste schema information into this conversation — you must never try to connect to a database directly.

WHEN I GIVE YOU SCHEMA DATA, PRODUCE THE FOLLOWING IN ORDER:

1. SOURCE-TO-TARGET MAPPING TABLE
Format as a table: | Source Column | Source Type | Target Column | Target Type | Transformation Required | Status |
Status values: DIRECT MAP / TRANSFORM / NO TARGET / NEW FIELD / EXCLUDE

2. ISSUES & RISKS LOG
| Issue | Severity (High/Medium/Low) | Column(s) Affected | Recommended Action |
Always flag as HIGH: Oracle DATE columns storing time, amounts in minor currency units (pence), Y/N CHAR needing BOOLEAN conversion, VARCHAR2 lengths that may truncate.

3. PII FLAGS
| Column | PII Category | Recommended Action |
Categories: Name, Contact Details, Financial, Identity, Location

ORACLE-SPECIFIC RULES to always apply:
- Oracle DATE = date + time. Flag if target is DATE not TIMESTAMP
- Y/N CHAR(1) → BOOLEAN at target
- Amounts in pence — flag divide-by-100 transformation
- Sequence PKs — note sequences must be re-seeded post-migration

Always end with: "Mapping complete. [X] columns mapped, [Y] issues found, [Z] PII fields flagged."</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- AGENT 7: PROCESS MAPPING -->
    <div class="agent-card reveal" id="ac7">
      <div class="agent-header" onclick="toggleAgent('ac7')">
        <div class="agent-icon tier-2"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><rect x="3" y="3" width="18" height="18" rx="2"/><line x1="3" y1="9" x2="21" y2="9"/><line x1="3" y1="15" x2="21" y2="15"/><line x1="9" y1="3" x2="9" y2="21"/><line x1="15" y1="3" x2="15" y2="21"/></svg></div>
        <div class="agent-header-text">
          <div class="agent-tier">Agent 07 <span class="tier-badge t2">Tier 2 — Setup needed</span></div>
          <div class="agent-name">Process Mapping Agent</div>
          <div class="agent-tagline">Describe a process verbally or paste in notes. The agent produces a structured process map with steps, decision points, owners, and handoffs — formatted for Visio or PowerPoint.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="agent-chevron"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></div>
      </div>
      <div class="agent-body">
        <div class="agent-grid">
          <div>
            <div class="agent-col-label">What it does</div>
            <div class="agent-col-body"><p>Takes a verbal or written description of a process and structures it into a formal process map with numbered steps, decision points (Yes/No branches), owners per step, system touchpoints, and handoff moments. Outputs in a format you can paste into Visio, PowerPoint, or Miro.</p></div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="agent-col-label">Data it needs</div>
            <div class="agent-col-body" style="display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:4px;align-content:flex-start">
              <div class="data-tag"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M21 15a2 2 0 01-2 2H7l-4 4V5a2 2 0 012-2h14a2 2 0 012 2z"/></svg>Process description</div>
              <div class="data-tag"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M14 2H6a2 2 0 00-2 2v16a2 2 0 002 2h12a2 2 0 002-2V8z"/></svg>Meeting notes (optional)</div>
              <p style="font-size:0.78rem;color:#888;margin-top:10px;line-height:1.5">You can describe the process directly in the chat, or upload interview notes / workshop outputs from SharePoint for the agent to structure.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="agent-col-label">How it helps on an engagement</div>
            <div class="agent-col-body"><p>Takes the raw output of a process workshop and turns it into a clean, structured map in minutes. Saves hours of Visio work and means your team can iterate faster with the client.</p></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="prompt-box">
          <div class="prompt-label">Suggestive system prompt</div>
          <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyPrompt(this)">Copy</button>
          <div class="prompt-text">"You are a process mapping assistant for consulting engagements. When I describe a process or provide workshop notes, structure it into a formal process map. For each step include: Step number, Step name, Description (one sentence), Owner / responsible role, System or tool used, Decision point (Yes/No/None), and Next step(s). Present it as a numbered list first, then describe the swimlane structure (which roles own which steps). Flag any ambiguous steps where you need clarification. At the end, note any inefficiencies or handoff risks you noticed."</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

<!-- PROMPT TIPS -->
<section class="prompt-section" id="prompts">
  <div class="prompt-inner">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Before you build</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Prompt Tips for Client Work</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">These agents are only as good as the instructions you give them. A few things that make a real difference when building for client delivery.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="prompt-cols reveal">
      <div class="prompt-col">
        <h3>What to always include <span class="do-tag">Do this</span></h3>
        <ul class="check-list good">
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Name the client and engagement so it knows the context</li>
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Specify the output format exactly — table, bullets, one-pager</li>
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Tell it what tone — professional, concise, client-facing</li>
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Tell it to flag gaps or uncertainties rather than guessing</li>
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Include what it should never do — e.g. "never include internal cost figures"</li>
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Give it an example of a good output if you have one</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="prompt-col">
        <h3>Common mistakes to avoid <span class="dont-tag">Don't do this</span></h3>
        <ul class="check-list bad">
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Being vague — "write a good summary" tells it nothing</li>
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Assuming it knows your client — always name them explicitly</li>
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Forgetting to specify length — you'll get walls of text</li>
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Not testing with real data before relying on it with a client</li>
          <li><div class="dot"></div>Uploading sensitive data without checking your firm's data policy first</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CHECKLIST -->
<section class="checklist-section" id="checklist">
  <div class="checklist-inner">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Before you leave</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Test Your Agent</h2>
      <p class="section-sub" style="margin-bottom:0">Run through these five checks before you demo or deploy your agent.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="cl-cards reveal">
      <div class="cl-card" onclick="toggleCheck(this)">
        <div class="cl-checkbox"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></div>
        <div class="cl-body">
          <div class="cl-num">01</div>
          <h3>It uses real data, not generic responses</h3>
          <p>"Ask it something that requires it to actually read your SharePoint or emails — not just something it could answer from general knowledge."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="cl-card" onclick="toggleCheck(this)">
        <div class="cl-checkbox"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></div>
        <div class="cl-body">
          <div class="cl-num">02</div>
          <h3>The output format is client-ready</h3>
          <p>"Would you be comfortable sending this output directly to a client, or does it need significant editing? If it needs heavy editing, improve the prompt."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="cl-card" onclick="toggleCheck(this)">
        <div class="cl-checkbox"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></div>
        <div class="cl-body">
          <div class="cl-num">03</div>
          <h3>It flags when it doesn't know something</h3>
          <p>"Ask it something it can't find in its data sources. It should say it doesn't know — not make something up. If it invents an answer, tighten your prompt."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="cl-card" onclick="toggleCheck(this)">
        <div class="cl-checkbox"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></div>
        <div class="cl-body">
          <div class="cl-num">04</div>
          <h3>It respects your boundaries</h3>
          <p>"Try asking it to do something outside its scope — e.g. share internal cost data. It should decline or redirect, not comply. If it doesn't, add a restriction to your instructions."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="cl-card" onclick="toggleCheck(this)">
        <div class="cl-checkbox"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg></div>
        <div class="cl-body">
          <div class="cl-num">05</div>
          <h3>You could demo it to a client today</h3>
          <p>"If someone asked you to show this to the client tomorrow morning, would you be comfortable? If not — what's the one thing you'd fix first?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="cl-progress reveal">
      <div class="cl-progress-bar"><div class="cl-progress-fill" id="progressFill"></div></div>
      <div class="cl-progress-label"><span id="progressCount">0</span> of 5 complete</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

